<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-789-382  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 789 382.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Oct 23 1989 n271 p20(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Users look to fiber. (outlook for fiber optic networks)(ComputerNetworking Closeup)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kass, Elliot M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Before jumping on the fiber-optic bandwagon, users must be surethat their companies need the expensive, leading-edge technology.andO;Fiber has many advantages.andP;  Compared to copper wire, it isthinner, lighter, more flexible, easier to install, uses lesspower and can transmit far more information, but it is also moreexpensive.andP;  Many organizations do not need fiber's capabilities.andO;For others, selective installation of fiber where needed may bethe best move.andP;  The newness of optical communications has meantthat the marketplace is confused, but the arrival of the FiberDistributed Data Interface (FDDI) standard should bring order tothat marketplace.andP;  Some manufacturers are frustrated, however, byANSI's delay in finalizing FDDI.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsFiber Distributed Data Interface StandardMarket AnalysisNew TechniqueHardware SelectionCablesANSIStandardization.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>